  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Laws:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money laundering criminal statute)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\n3. Regulatory Agencies Involved:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Department of Justice (DOJ)\n\n4. Specific Requirements:\n- Reporting cash transactions over $10,000\n- Suspicious activity reporting\n- Customer identification programs\n- Enhanced due diligence for high-risk transactions\n\nThese statutes provide legal frameworks for preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering activities across various financial sectors.\n\nState-level laws may also exist that complement federal money laundering statutes, providing additional mechanisms for combating financial crimes.",
